==Old English==
===Spellings===
cnēo, cnēow

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*knewa-'', from Indo-European ''*genu-, *gneu-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[kniu]], Old Saxon [[knio]] (Dutch [[knie]]), Old High German [[kneo]] (German [[Knie]]), Old Norse [[kné]] (Swedish [[knä]]), Gothic [[𐌺𐌽𐌹𐌿]].  The IE root is also the source of Sanskrit [[जानु]], Avestan ''žnūm-'', Armenian ''cunr'', Albanian [[gju]], Greek [[γονυ]], Latin [[genu]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /kne:o/

===Noun===
'''cnēo''' ''n''
# the [[knee]]
#:''Hie on cneowum sæton'': they sat on their knees.
# a [[generation]]
#:''On anum cneowe'': in one generation.

